I did 
```
ln -s hello.c hello-link.c
gcc -g hello-link.c -o hello-link
```
then loaded hello-link in gdbgui. gdb returns breakpoints and source files indicating hello.c is the `fullfile` that was used, but it also indicates the `file` is `hello-link.c`. gdbgui has never used `file`, and that is why the `-data-disassemble` command is incorrect.

```
{
    "type": "result",
    "message": "done",
    "payload": {
        "files": [
            {
                "file": "hello-link.c",
                "fullname": "/Users/cssmith/git/gdbgui/examples/c/hello.c"
            },
            {
                "file": "/usr/include/i386/_types.h",
                "fullname": "/usr/include/i386/_types.h"
            },
            {
                "file": "/usr/include/sys/_types/_size_t.h",
                "fullname": "/usr/include/sys/_types/_size_t.h"
            }
        ]
    },
    "token": null,
    "stream": "stdout"
}
```

So I think what I should do is test if file and fullname are not equal, and if not, attempt to construct the true fullfile based on path replacement. So gdbgui would have a reconstructed fullfile of `/Users/cssmith/git/gdbgui/examples/c/hello-link.c`. What do you think?

